Try the following:

    [style.background-color]=&quot;&#39;red&#39;&quot;

Or:

    &lt;button [style.backgroundColor]=&quot;&#39;red&#39;&quot;&gt;&lt;/button&gt;

If you want to use variable instead of `red` then you do not need `&#39;` to wrap it with single quotes. You can define variable in your TS logic and assign value to it.

If you are using `red` as string then it&#39;s better you use CSS for it. The purpose of binding is to change the style based on the logic or whatever value your variable holds. 

For instance: You are checking if `canSave` is true then apply cyan color if false apply grey color.

    &lt;button [style.background-color]=&quot;canSave ? &#39;cyan&#39;: &#39;grey&#39;&quot; &gt;Save&lt;/button&gt;

You have done a style binding. Since you use red as string, you should wrap that string with `&quot;&quot;`  
  

    [style.backgroundColor]=&quot;&#39;red&#39;&quot;

else, you can define a variable in ts,

    colorRed =&#39;red&#39;

then bind it in html
 

    [style.backgroundColor]=&#39;colorRed&#39;

