A stream contains two &quot;pointers&quot; that point to the position where it is reading and where it is writing. If you are writing, then the read pointer is also advanced. So
you first want to move the read pointer backwards the amount of bytes you are going to read with [seekg()](https://en.cppreference.com/w/cpp/io/basic_istream/seekg):

`cfile.seekg(-static_cast&lt;long&gt;(sizeof stud), cfile.cur);`

#MRE / proof of concept

```
#include &lt;iostream&gt;
#include &lt;fstream&gt;

struct Foo {
	int i = 2;
	double d = 3.13421;
	float f = 3241.41f;
};

std::ostream&amp; operator&lt;&lt;(std::ostream&amp; s, const Foo&amp; foo) {
	return s &lt;&lt; &quot;i=&quot; &lt;&lt; foo.i &lt;&lt; &quot;; d=&quot; &lt;&lt; foo.d &lt;&lt; &quot;; f=&quot; &lt;&lt; foo.f;
}

int main() {
	std::fstream file;
	Foo foo;

	file.open(&quot;foo.txt&quot;, file.in | file.out | file.trunc);

	file &lt;&lt; &quot;some other text&quot;;

	file.write(reinterpret_cast&lt;char*&gt;(&amp;foo), sizeof foo);

	std::cout &lt;&lt; foo &lt;&lt; std::endl;

	foo.i = foo.d = foo.f = 0;

	file.seekg(-static_cast&lt;long&gt;(sizeof foo), file.cur);

	std::cout &lt;&lt; foo &lt;&lt; std::endl;

	file.read(reinterpret_cast&lt;char*&gt;(&amp;foo), sizeof foo);

	std::cout &lt;&lt; foo &lt;&lt; std::endl;
}
```

produces the following output:
```
i=2; d=3.13421; f=3241.41
i=0; d=0; f=0
i=2; d=3.13421; f=3241.41
```

